The best approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package rather than writing custom wrappers — it's battle-tested and covers your exact statics.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
# Production project
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions

# Test project
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs / Startup.cs
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

// ReadAllText
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));

// WriteAllText
manager.Save("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

// Directory.Exists
Assert.True(manager.EnsureDirectory("/data"));
Assert.False(manager.EnsureDirectory("/nonexistent"));
```

### Key points

- **Don't roll your own wrapper** — `System.IO.Abstractions` already covers `File.*`, `Directory.*`, `Path.*`, and more.
- `MockFileSystem` is an in-memory filesystem — no temp files, no cleanup, tests run fast.
- Register as **singleton** since `FileSystem` is stateless.

Once you've adopted the interface, use the **migrate-static-to-wrapper** skill (just ask!) to bulk-replace all `File.*` / `Directory.*` call sites across your project.
